{"answer": "The critic's case rests on a mathematical misreading of the target's inequality and conflates two distinct forbidden arms. Addressing each clause:\n\n(1) The critic claims precision < 0.5 is 'unreachable' because the inequality recall_wrong > (1 - precision) * fraction_right purportedly 'requires precision >= 0.5 for any feasible recall_wrong <= 1 when the right-majority fraction is non-trivial.' This is false arithmetic. With fraction_right = p_right_majority: the bound is recall_wrong > (1 - precision) * p_right_majority. At precision = 0.3, p_right_majority = 0.5, the RHS is 0.35, satisfied by any recall_wrong > 0.35 — well within [0,1]. At precision = 0.1, p_right_majority = 0.4, RHS = 0.36, again feasible. The critic's 'requires precision >= 0.5' only holds if p_right_majority approaches 1, which is explicitly not the case in the intermediate regime (base error 0.40-0.55 yields substantial p_wrong_majority). No impossibility is established.\n\n(2) The target's forbidden case #2 specifies base error 0.40-0.55 AND critic precision < 0.5 AND harness accuracy >= self-consistency on >= 50% of questions. This is a legitimate negative-control arm: it tests whether low-precision critics harm performance in a regime where wrong majorities exist. The scope's 'covers: critic precision >= 0.5' defines the primary hypothesis region; the forbidden arm with precision < 0.5 is the complementary falsification test. There is no contradiction between covering the >= 0.5 region for the main claim and specifying a < 0.5 arm as a forbidden case — these are different experimental arms, not the same arm required to simultaneously satisfy contradictory constraints.\n\n(3) The critic's reliance on std-crit-design clause (3) ('Proposals whose forbidden cases cannot be measured by rerunning this repository's validation harness violate this standard') is inapplicable because the forbidden case IS measurable: the decisive experiment in prose_notes explicitly constructs base-error bins at 0.45 (within 0.40-0.55), and nothing prevents a critic with precision < 0.5 from being measured on those questions. The validation harness can record critic precision/recall stratified by majority correctness and compare harness vs. self-consistency accuracy per bin. The arm is generable and measurable.\n\n(4) The critic provides no evidence that the repository's harness cannot produce or evaluate critics with precision < 0.5. The target's own mechanism cites measured precision of 0.125 in v4-pro hard, demonstrating that sub-0.5 precision critics are not only possible but already observed. The critic concedes nothing against this — because nothing establishes infeasibility.\n\nThe critic's case fails: the inequality does not force precision >= 0.5 in the intermediate regime, the two forbidden arms are distinct rather than self-contradictory, and the < 0.5 arm is both generable and measurable by the described harness."}